A sub-sub-section (Traditions and Innovations) has been added.

This contribution is by no means "refspam", but is a concise information of research projects carried out by ethnomusicologist Dr. Alexander Rosenblatt over the past fifteen years on a little-studied topic - the music of contemporary Christian denominations and communities (mainly in Israel and Pacific Northwest). Five references are to articles published in academic journals that can be found and read using a Google search, and another link refers to a public domain collection of Maronite music

A new subsection "Sa Le'at" (that include a quotation and a rephrased summary, all with references to particular pages in the journal article) is added in within the section "Music Career," after "'The Old and Good Land of Israel' albums" section.

(1) The citation from the journal article is now made a block-quote with a reference and researcher's name in the text. Page numbers are indicated for an exact quotation (pp. 272–273) and for a rephrased summary (p. 274), provided that this is researcher's consideration; (2) "Ehud Manor" replaces "he" in the existed sentence that immediately follows new material.
(1) Expanding a line about one song to a whole paragraph (with a reference to the source); (2) Replacing "he" with "Ehud Manor" in the existing sentence that now follows this paragraph.
Correction of the reference to one source.

A “Christian music today” section has been added, in which: (1) the small subsection "Modern" (formerly the last in the “History” section) has been moved to the top of the “Christian music today” section and renamed "Modern trends"; (2) added a large subsection  "Traditions and innovations worldwide" with reference to five sources.

1) In the section "Forms", second paragraph of sub-heading Digital Ethnography was added; 2) In the section "Ethics", a sub-section "Who owns ethnography" was added; 3) The section "New Practices and Information Spaces" that includes three subsections was added. The material was supported by references to five sources (articles in academic journals).
